The Model Context Protocol (MCP) is the standardized agent protocol for Adobe Commerce (Magento), allowing AI assistants like Claude, Cursor, and Windsurf to interact directly with your store [1][2][3]. It enables AI to perform tasks like catalog management, diagnostics, and order processing by executing tools—typically via GraphQL or REST APIs—without manual data exports [1][4][2].

Multiple implementations exist to suit different needs:

Standardized administration servers, such as those from thomastx05/magento-mcp, offer 30+ tools for catalog and promotion management, featuring two-phase commits, audit logging, and built-in guardrails for safety [1][5].

Developer-focused servers, such as @rafaelcg/adobe-commerce-dev-mcp, provide schema introspection for both GraphQL and REST APIs and assist in writing or validating integrations [6][7].

Lightweight proxy services, such as the one documented at mcp-hub.ink, map RESTful requests to GraphQL operations to simplify automation for agents [4].

To connect an MCP client, add the server configuration to your `mcp_config.json` or `claude_desktop_config.json` file. For a Node.js-based server, use the following pattern:

```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "magento-mcp": {
      "command": "node",
      "args": ["/path/to/server/dist/index.js"],
      "env": {
        "MAGENTO_BASE_URL": "https://your-instance.com",
        "MAGENTO_OAUTH_CONSUMER_KEY": "your_key",
        "MAGENTO_OAUTH_CONSUMER_SECRET": "your_secret",
        "MAGENTO_OAUTH_TOKEN": "your_token",
        "MAGENTO_OAUTH_TOKEN_SECRET": "your_token_secret"
      }
    }
  }
}
```

Security is typically managed via Magento ACL integration, ensuring AI access is restricted to authorized API permissions [1][2]. Many implementations also use OAuth 1.0 or 2.0 to bypass 2FA prompts while keeping credentials in memory [1][2].
